Excellent! Now I can see that `DBFieldAttribute` has a `references` property:

```typescript
references?: {
  model: string;    // The model to reference (e.g., "user")
  field: string;    // The field on the referenced model (e.g., "id")
  onDelete?: "no action" | "restrict" | "cascade" | "set null" | "set default";
}
```

And `BetterAuthDBSchema` is:
```typescript
Record<string, {
  modelName: string;     // The table name in the DB
  fields: Record<string, DBFieldAttribute>;
  disableMigrations?: boolean;
  order?: number;
}>
```

So the schema uses default model and field names as keys, but each model also has a `modelName` property that maps to the actual database table name. The adapter callback gets the full schema with those default names, plus a `getModelName()` helper to look up the actual table names when needed.

Now I'm checking what the adapter methods actually receive ÔÇö whether they get the default names or the database names. The adapter methods seem to receive the database table and column names directly, along with helper functions to convert back to defaults. Let me trace through the transformation logic to confirm how the data flows through `transformInput`, `transformOutput`, and `transformWhereClause`. I need to look at the actual factory implementation to understand what transformations it applies automatically versus what the adapter creator is responsible for.

